(The behaviour of a division by zero is undefined in standard C++, although IEEE754 does define the behaviour for floating point types.)

If you use `throw`, then you also need to provide a corresponding `catch`.

But as you don&#39;t need to do that in this case (you are already issuing errors to the console) a simple
  
    if (!num2){
        std::cerr &lt;&lt; &quot;division by zero&quot;;
    }

in the part of the code that computes the division would be sufficient.

Your branch `else if (calculation == 0)` is also a bug since there&#39;s nothing to initialise `calculation`, but my fix removes the need for that.

Just check if `num2` is equals to zero if the char is `/`. You have an runtime exception on row 
```
else if (symb == &#39;/&#39;){
   cacluation = num1 / num2;
}
```
if num2 is zero.

This is wrong:
```
else if (cacluation == 0 ) {
     throw error;
}
```
It could be zero divided by anything but zero. It will be a zero as an answer. You are wrong.

```
else if (symb == &#39;/&#39;){
    if (num2 ==0)
        cout&lt;&lt;&quot;Mathematical error&quot;;
    else
        calcluation = num1 / num2;
}
    
  ```

At very first, you have undefined behaviour in your programme:

    int cacluation; // uninitialised!
    if (...) { }
    else if (...) { }
    // ...
    else if (cacluation == 0) // &lt;- (!)
    {
        // ...
    }

If all those previous checks failed (i. e. user did not enter a valid symbol), you are now evaluating the uninitialised variable `calculation`!

Apart from, this check would be incorrect anyway, assume user entering `1 + -1` or `1 - 1`...

What you indeed need to do is checking the divisor *before* executing the calculation, and you only do so if user actually wants to divide:

    // ...
    else if (symb == &#39;/&#39;)
    {
        // check BEFORE calculation:
        if(num2 == 0)
        {
            // appropriate error handling, e. g. print some error message
        }
        else
        {
            cacluation = num1 / num2;
        }
    }

Finally, you&#39;d yet need to avoid printing out the invalid result. A pretty simple way would be replacing the assignment to `calculation` variable with outputting the value directly:

    else
    {
        std::cout &lt;&lt; num1 / num2; // analogously in all other branches
    }

